summary:
Special issue of The Journal of Architecture 2020, vol. 25, issue 8. Eds. Petra Brouwer, Kristina Jõekalda.

///

Informed by postcolonial theory and more recent attempts to write alternative global histories of art and architecture, scholars have increasingly criticised the persistence of the canon and its Eurocentric perspective, questioning related categories, narratives, and terminology. The aim of this special issue is to contribute to a more nuanced understanding of historiography by analysing Eurocentrism in the writing of architectural histories from the inside; that is, from the less researched perspective of Europe’s own ‘margins’. We argue that it was the very method of nineteenth- and twentieth-century architectural history writing that conceptualised a binary world of exemplary and marginal architecture. The idea of a small core of historically and aesthetically representative monuments, and a large periphery of insignificant buildings was inextricably bound up with architectural history’s grand narrative of progress and modernisation. With accounts from Finland, Greece, Portugal, the Netherlands, and Switzerland, this special issue breaks up the trope of Europe in a heterogeneous geopolitical and architectural landscape to address the troublesome relationship between the local, the national, and the general. In particular, we are concerned with looking anew at two recurrent historiographical debates that continue to shape the architectural image of the edges of Europe: (1) the paradigm of centre–periphery relations and its effect on architectural histories; and (2) critical regionalism’s claim of rewriting the history of modern architecture from the point of view of local and national cultural identities.
